funding_code: RURAL COOPERATIVE DEVELOPMENT GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to workers-owned cooperative groups located in rural areas. Project includes assistance for at least 78 cooperatives as well as work with organizing groups made up of Native American and Native Alaskan organizations working on cooperative projects mainly in rural California, Alaska, and South Dakota. This funds will help create 17 and save 41 rural jobs in California. In addition, the organization is projecting to assist at least 70 rural businesses which will create a number of rural jobs.

funding_code: DISCRETION ASSIST MICROPENTERPRENUERS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide microloans to help startup and stablish small businesses in various rural areas using Rural Microloan Revolving Fund. This funds will help create 10 and save 10 rural jobs.

funding_code: DISCRETIONARY RMAP LOANS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to rural micro-entrepreneurs and microenterprises that have received or are seeking one or more microloans from the micro lender. This includes marketing, management, and other forms of technical assistance needed. This funds will help at least one rural business and create 10 job and save 10 rural jobs.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY GRANTS TO ASSIST MINORITY PRODUCERS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to worker and producer Cooperative development for socially disadvantage rural groups such as; Native Americans, Native Alaskans, Latino Youth and women. The fund will help several persistent poverty counties and remote communities to create and save rural jobs.

funding_code: (WWA PROGRAM AREA) SOLID WASTE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance and training through direct and indirect assistance to 26 California, seven Arizona, 13 Nevada and four New Mexico federally recognized Tribes to reduce their solid waste streams. The project will accomplish this task by providing one-on-one direct consultations, workshops and tutorials with rural and remote Tribes that fit the criteria including population, median household income, poverty levels, and underserved trust areas. The project is designed to empower tribal environmental programs and governments with tools and training that increase innovation in problem solving while improving their waste management infrastructure and protecting Tribal environments.

funding_code: (WWA PROGRAM AREA) TAT GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance and training through direct and indirect assistance to 26 California, 7 Arizona, 13 Nevada and 14 New Mexico federally recognized Tribes to reduce their solid waste stream.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE NATIVE AMERICAN GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
naics_description: AMERICAN INDIAN AND ALASKA NATIVE TRIBAL GOVERNMENTS
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide training and technical assistance to small, rural, tribal-member owned enterprises located on reservations in Calif. It develops rural learning programs that provide educational instruction to existing and prospective entrepreneurs and adults that are seeking to increase their skills to gain employment or increase their likelihood of job advancements. The training will consist of business planning, computer literacy and skills development, personal and business financial literacy, and leadership development training.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist a hog rancher who is located in Amador County, California. The grant funding will go to pay for value added processing, supplies, and sales labor.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide direct marketing technical assistance to microenterprise businesses located in rural communities that meet the income threshold designated by the Community Services Block Grant Act. The services will include developing web sites, create e-commerce platforms, conduct market and client demand research, and/or understand regulatory and policy standards for 20 small businesses that requires assistance for survival and growth. The project service area includes the Counties of Butte, Glenn, Colusa, Lake and Tehama.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development will be used to help Ed Dutro Corporation purchase and installation a 100.75 kW Solar Renewable Energy System located in Chico, California. This fund will help to reduce the energy costs and reduce the carbonfootprint with renewable and energy efficiency system.

funding_code: LAMP VALUE ADDED PRODUCER GRANT MANDATORY
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist a wine grape farmer in Butte County, California. Grant funds of $250,000 will be used to pay for value added processing, packaging materials, and marketing.

funding_code: LOCAL AGRICULTURE MARKET RESOURCE PROGRAM (LAMP) VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER GRANTS - COVID
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist a rice farmer who is located in Durham, Butte County, California. This fund of $250,000 will go to pay for value-added processing, packaging materials, and marketing of their rice product. The fund will help save one job in this rural community.

funding_code: VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER DEVELOPMENT GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Sohnrey Family Foods LLC, an almond farming business, pay for value added processing labor and the marketing of its almond butter flavors. Fund is expected to help five farmers.

funding_code: LAMP BEGINNING AND SOCIALLY DISADVANTAGED FARMERS OR RANCHERS GRANTS - COVID
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
naics_description: FATS AND OILS REFINING AND BLENDING
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help an olive farmer who produces olive oil in Butte County, California. Grant funds of $250,000 will be used to pay for value added processing, packaging, and marketing. The fund will help save three rural jobs.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Kimshew District Cemetary conduct repairs, replace equipment, and restore buildings damaged in the disastrous 2018 Camp Fire. Kimshew District Cemetary will remove four cedar trees and one oak tree that are considered harzadous. Additionally, the district will repair and rehabiltate sections of its fence, irrigation systems, a pump and pump house and the power supply to the pump station. The grant will be used to purchase a truck, a mower, and other various pieces of equipment for routine maintenance and funerals. The office and shop exteriors will be painted. These improvements and new equipment will allow the facility to return to operation as soon as possible. As the dangers of dead-falls and dry, unirrigated, flammable undergrowth fuels are a hazard to health and safety to the surrounding areas, this USDA grant will go far to protect the community.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a 130kw generator and install a 1200amp transfer switch at Spring Valley School in Butte County. After the Camp Fire of 2018, all of the students from the burned Concow School were transferred to this facility. The generator is critical to keep the schools open during potential PSPS events providing power for critical facilities such as: communications, cafeteria, and cooling systems. The districts students have already lost an unacceptable amount of educational time due to the Camp Fire in 2018 and now the COVID-19 pandemic. It is the Districts desire to keep them in school as much as possible given the trying conditions.

borrower_name: BOYS & GIRLS CLUBS OF THE NORTH VALLEY
funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase of a 10-passenger van and enrichment equipment, including coding and 3D printing units, which will allow the teen center at the high school to assist the educational needs and transportation of the students in rural areas. This will allow the organization to expand their much-needed support and mentoring services to the low income and at-risk youth in the rural surrounding areas of Oroville, California.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER PUBLIC BUILDING & IMPROVEMENT RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Palermo Union Elementary School District purchase two portable bus chargers. The district currently operates two electric buses that are normally charged at their bus barn. Unfortunately, this site is often included in state-mandated Public Safety Power Shutoff (PSPS) events resulting in loss of electrical service. This grant will allow the district to move the electric bus fleet to one of their other sites that has not been part of the PSPS. This will be critical to keeping the buses running and the schools open during potential PSPS events. The districts students have already lost an unacceptable amount of educational time due to the camp fire in 2018 and now the COVID-19 pandemic.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - 2018 WILDFIRES
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase nine portable radios for the town of Paradises law enforcement department. These radios will directly connect with the Butte County and CaIOES radio networks. The past destruction of the towns law enforcement radio sites required law enforcement, EMS and Public Works to contract with Butte Country to provide radio access. Butte country has now upgraded their system to the new P25 standard. Paradises equipment is incompatible with that system threatening law enforcement and EMS services. These new all-band, P25 radios will greatly improve Paradises communication and emergency response capacity.

funding_code: RRH-NONSUBSIDIZED-SEC538 GUARANTEED
naics_industry_sector: Real Estate and Rental and Leasing (53)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist in the transfer, assumption and rehabilitation of Oroville Manor, an existing senior multi-family housing complex in Oroville, CA. The project consists of 71 one-bedroom and 1 two-bedroom units. All units will go through significant rehabilitation and improve the living conditions for all current and future tenants.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)

naics_description: OFFICES OF PHYSICIANS (EXCEPT MENTAL HEALTH SPECIALISTS)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a medical facility. It will help El Dorado County Community Health Center, a non-profit Federally Qualified Health Center, better serve rural residents of Placerville and the surrounding area. The centers buildings in Placerville and Diamond Springs will be combined into a 30,642-square-foot, single-story building. The center is a key player in the distribution of COVID vaccines in El Dorado County. It also provides medical, behavioral health, dental, pharmacy and substance misuse treatment services.

funding_code: MAND. RENEW ENERFY SYSTEMS GRANTS UNDER $20,000
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Jennifer Simone purchase a 23 kilowatt (kW) solar array to offset electrical costs of normal operations. Jenniffer Simone is a sole proprietor farmer growing almond trees and producing almonds for processing through area hulling operations and then for sale. High energy cost comprises a large part of the business operating expenses. This project will save $9,050 per year and replace 36,200 kilowatts (kW) per year, which is enough electricity to power three homes per year.

funding_code: ECONOMIC IMPACT INITIATIVE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase equipment for an internet extension to provide free internet access to additional 220 families of students in the community. This project is essential due to COVID-19 pandemic and the need for distance learning. Students will be able to connect to the schools internet and to complete their daily school lessons at no cost to the students families. Without this equipment, it would be very difficult, and in some areas impossible for the student to complete online classwork. The communities served are: Tranquillity, San Joaquin, Cantua Creek, and Three Rocks. Affordable internet is not available in all of these communities.

naics_description: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to purchase equipment for an internet extension to provide free internet access to an additional 220 families of students in the community. This project is essential due to COVID-19 pandemic and the need for distance learning. Students will be able to connect to the schools internet and to complete their daily school lessons at no cost to the students families. Without this equipment, it would be very difficult, and in some areas impossible for the student to complete online classwork. The communities served are: Tranquillity, San Joaquin, Cantua Creek and Three Rocks. Affordable internet is not available in all of these communities.

funding_code: MAND. RENEW ENERFY SYSTEMS GRANTS UNDER $20,000
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist farmers, ranchers, and rural small businesses in developing renewable energy systems, and in making energy-efficiency improvements to their operations. funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help the city of Orland to purchase a new Pierce Enforcer Type I Fire Engine with a 1500 gpm pump to replace a critically needed fire engine. The Type I Fire Engine will transport six firefighters to the emergency scene safely and enhance the capabilities of the Orland Fire Department. The engine will protect lives. Without it, Orlands firefighters and citizens are at significant risk for injury and property loss. The old equipment is no longer mechanically dependable, nor is it efficient or safe for firefighter transportation. Without the assistance of the grant, it would be a financial struggle for the city of Orland to purchase this piece of equipment. While the Fire Department has worked diligently to be as fiscally conservative as possible and continuously save for purchases such as this, without the USDA CF program the equipment fund would be completely depleted, leaving no funds for potential emergency future needs.

funding_code: DISCRETION ASSIST MICROPENTERPRENUERS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to microentrepreneurs and microenterprises that are located within the Micro Development Organizations service area. Technical assistance will be available to applicants, potential applicants and existing borrowers that have received loans from the MDO under their Rural Microloan Revolving Loan Fund. This fund will help 10 small businesses and will help create 10 new and save 10 existing rural jobs.

funding_code: COMBINATION CF DIRECT LOAN/GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to to purchase the existing property that has provided successful therapeutic equine programs for children. The property, located in Fortuna, California, has allowed Wild Souls Ranch to triple revenue and they currently have a six-month waiting list, as the program has been very successful. The youth who attend Wild Souls Ranch come to heal from childhood trauma and benefit from equine assisted growth and learning. The ability to own the facility will allow Wild Souls Ranch cost stability over the upkeep of the facility, which includes keeping pastures clean and well maintained, mending fences, as well as maintaining the pen areas. Furthermore, the ability to own the property will allow Wild Souls Ranch to expand programs and allow for more children to enroll in these very successful programs.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the HVAC system for two at Dream it. Be it. These classrooms are currently serviced by a system which is not properly sealed which has a negative effect on air quality. The investment will support the purchase of new ventilation and air filter systems which will provide an improved learning environment for students.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a new fire pumper engine that will be used to combat fires in an area where fires have increased dramatically over the years. The new fire pumper engine will be equipped the new technology making it easier for Fortuna Fire Protection District to communicate with other fire districts. The new fire pumper engine will be able to respond more effectively to fires.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This rural development investment will be used to purchase two new police vehicles that will be custom built for the needs of the City of Fortuna. The new police vehicles will be equipped with better doors, window guards, and partitions to make it safe for transporting the prisoners. The new vehicles will be able to provide safe transportation for officers and respond quicker to emergencies.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development will be used to purchase a new Vac Con Truck that will be custom built for the needs of the city of Fortuna. This Vac Truck will have one diesel engine which will allow the city of Fortuna to operate the Vac Truck without the use of a diesel permit which will allow for quicker operations. The ability to have one diesel engine will reduce emissions and provide a safe environment for staff. The Vac Con truck will provide safer operations for employees such as not having to do emergency digs by hand which could lead to staff hitting unmarked lines such as electrical or gas lines and lead to serious injury for staff.

project_name: 2021 PPE GEAR & JAWS OF LIFE F
funding_code: ECONOMIC IMPACT INITIATIVE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase 20 sets of personal protective equipment structural equipment that would allow firefighters to reduce their cancer exposure and to better serve their community in a more efficient manner. Currently, each member of the department is given one set of gear, exposing themselves to cancer fumes after every call. Proper procedure would be to wash the gear after each fire and allow it to air out for at least two hours. The second set of gear would allow the firefighters to be able and respond to another call without exposing themselves to cancerous fumes. In addition to the PPE the following equipment will also be purchased; a set of Auto Extrication Forcible Entry Tools (Jaws of Life), to reduce the time of response to aid in automobile collision and thus being increasing the chances to save lives, and 14 sets of PPE wildland gear to help firefighters fight wildfires. The gear will allow the crews to prolong their quality of life and reduce on the job injury.

funding_code: ECONOMIC IMPACT INITIATIVE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase two golf carts which will replace their current carts. The golf carts have outlived their lifespans and need to be replaced. The carts are used by the maintenance and operation staff for carrying tools and materials throughout both campuses. They break down and the batteries need to be replaced often. The 280 HP Chromebooks, with cases will be used to finalize their one-to-one devise implementation and it will allow the district to replace devices which are at the end of life. The proposed equipment is essential to allow the district to increase the efficiency of the transportation, maintenance and operations, and the district as a whole, which may reduce expenses to HESD. Cost savings will allow HESD to reallocate funds to improving and enhancing educational services further improving the quality of education for their students.

funding_code: ECONOMIC IMPACT INITIATIVE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase two trucks and one six passenger van to transport students. The new vehicles will replace the current aging vehicles which have outlived their lifespan. The original purpose of the truck was to be able to drive for pickups at local venders. However, as it deteriorated, it was not used for that purpose. The need for a usable small pickup to make trips to our various vendors to pick up supplies. With limited deliver services, these trucks will help immensely. The van which is being proposed will replace the current van. The van is used to transport students to the Vista Sands programs as well as used for athletics. The proposed equipment is essential to allow the District to increase the efficiency of the transportation, Maintenance and Operations, and the District as a whole, which may reduce expenses to HESD. Cost savings will allow HESD to reallocate funds to improving and enhancing educational services further improving the quality of education for their students.

funding_code: ECONOMIC IMPACT INITIATIVE GRANTS

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used for purchasing outdoor picnic tables and the installation of a shaded concrete patio to the newly constructed community center. The proposed equipment will be utilized by the HESD to provide creative studio sessions, summer school SMART academy classes, and After School Education and Safety (ASES) activities.

funding_code: ECONOMIC IMPACT INITIATIVE GRANTS

funding_code: ECONOMIC IMPACT INITIATIVE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase 28 sets of Personal Protective Equipment Wildland Gear that would allow firefighters to help fight wildfire and protect their wellbeing; and two sets of Auto Extrication Forcible Entry tools to better serve this community in a more efficient manner. Currently, each member of the department is given one set of gear, exposing themselves to cancer fumes after each wildfire occurrence. Given the current situation of wildfires, the Department must be prepared to assist other Fire Districts help fight wildfires and the second set of Wildland PPE gear will alleviate the need to longer lengths of dangerous fumes to the firefighters. Placing the departments mission first and providing the ideal service to those that we serve. The gear would allow firefighter crews to prolong their quality of life and reduce on the job injury.

project_name: 2019 Well Replacement & Water Plant Improvement Project
funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) 306C  WATER ONLY (COLONIAS)
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to install approximately 4,100 feet of eight inch polyvinyl chloride (PVC) sewer main and install manholes along Monroe Street near the Torres-Martinez Desert Cahuilla Indian Reservation in southwestern Riverside County. The eight inch sewer main will be connected to an existing 33-inch sewer main, owned and operated by the Coachella Valley Water District (CVWD). The new sewer main will connect a subdivision, church, and community building located within the Torres-Martinez Desert Cahuilla Indian Reservation to the existing sewer collection system operated by CVWD. The housing units and facilities that will connect to the new sewer main currently discharge sewage into septic tanks located on each property. The Torres-Martinez Desert Cahuilla Indian tribe has determined that these tanks are failing and have caused seepage of sewage to ground water and in cases sewage has been detected above ground. The proposed project will allow the Tribe to abandon the failing septic tanks and allow them to connect to CVWDs existing sewage treatment system.

program: SEARCH - Special Evaluation Assistance for Rural Communities and Households Grant (WEP)
funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) SEARCH GRANTS WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assess the problems on well #2. Winterhaven water facility is currently operating off one well. Winterhaven County Water District is currently not in compliance with several components of their water treatment and distribution system with a second well that is not operational due to a lot of sand getting in the well casing.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development loan guarantee will be used to provide long-term financing for a 5.617 MW(DC) solar farm on property located at Corcoran, Kings County, California The borrower is a newly-formed entity and the fund will be used for purchase and installation of a solar power generation facility to export and sell electricity.The system is estimated to produce 5,617,000 kilowatt hours (kWh) per year, which is enough electricity to power 890 homes.

Improvements include new pipelines, water tanks, back flow meters, and other necessary equipment that is vital for a secure water supply for the users of the Clearlake Oaks County Water District.

funding_code: COMBINATION CF DIRECT LOAN/GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an existing school campus, renovations, and the construction of a new 6,000-sq-ft gym/multi-purpose building with handicapped accessible restrooms. Long Valley Charter School is a nonprofit public benefit corporation (LVCS) that operates two charter schools. Each school is recognized as a Local Education Agency (LEA) by the State of California, providing educational programs for grades TK-12. The project will be located in Doyle, California, Lassen County, a designated distressed community. Doyle is also in a Health Professional Shortage Area for Mental Health and a Medically Underserved Area. For the Service Area, Charter Schools can supply services to students in the county where they are located and any contiguous county. Under these parameters, the school could provide educational services to students in the rural communities of Lassen, Modoc, Plumas, Shasta, and Sierra Counties. However, because of the distances involved services are mainly restricted to Lassen and Plumas Counties. The school was originally started because the school district decided to close the Doyle location and the parents in the community did not want to bus their children to another community. LVCS originally planned for the construction of a new education facility in the community of Doyle. The new facilities had a planned gross building area of 17,757 square feet. The application was complete when the Board of Directors decided that they should pursue the purchase of the existing facilities they were renting from the Fort Sage School District. The School Board felt it was worth it to support the community with the remodeling of the existing school rather than let it go vacant and into disrepair. The new project will include the construction of a new multipurpose room and the installation of two new modular classrooms. The gross area of the existing facilities is 16,444 square feet and includes 10 classrooms, a library, two offices, a multipurpose room, kitchen, five storage areas and 10 restrooms. The facilities have a parking area and bus loading area, two basketball courts, a soccer field, a volleyball court, two playgrounds and extensive irrigated landscaping. The new construction will include a 6,100-sq-ft gym and two accessible restrooms and a storage area. The total gross building area upon completion will be approximately 24,463 square feet per the appraisal.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used for the purchase and installation of three 1.088 MWdc solar power generation system in each facility to export and sell electricity. CA Solar Holdco, LLC (Borrower) is an entity that was formed specifically to own the subject utility scale solar projects located in Corcoran, Ca, Madera, CA and Le Grand, CA. naics_industry_sector: Real Estate and Rental and Leasing (53)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to acquire and rehabilitate Cantamar Villas, a Section 515 multi-family housing complex in Avalon, California. The project will go through significant rehabilitation and improve the living conditions for all the current and future tenants. The property consists of four two-story apartment buildings located over four parcels at two scattered sites (Beacon Hill & Bird Park Apartments) and is collectively known as Cantamar Villas. Beacon Hill Apartments, at 309 Beacon Street contains 13 one-bedroom units and is restricted to senior tenants and Bird Park Apartments, located at 234 Bird Park Road contains 25 units consisting of seven two-bedroom, 16 three-bedroom and two four-bedroom units and is a family development.

funding_code: GUARANTEED B&I 3% FEE LOAN
naics_industry_sector: Accommodation and Food Services (72)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to refinance and real estate improvement of a21-room boutique hotel located in Little River, CA. The fund will help to refinancetwo loans to improve cash flow. This project will help create two full time jobs, as well as save seven additional jobs in the small rural community of Little River, CA.

funding_code: GUARANTEED B&I 3% FEE LOAN
naics_industry_sector: Accommodation and Food Services (72)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to refinance a 14-room boutique motel and a mixed-use building property located in Point Arena, CA. This refinance will help provide a better interest rate & permanent financing for the borrower and will help save up to $143,473 annually on interest payment. In addition, this fund will help create 5 and save 5 rural jobs and will support economic growth in this rural community.

funding_code: GUARANTEED B&I 3% FEE LOAN
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to refinance a winery operation located at Ukiah, CA.This fund will go to refinance two third party loans which will help the company save approximately $79,812 per year and save 74 rural jobs.

funding_code: DISCRETION ASSIST MICROPENTERPRENUERS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to microentrepreneurs and microenterprises that are located within the Micro Development Organizations (MDOs) service area. Technical assistance will be available to applicants, potential applicants and existing borrowers that have received loans from the MDO under their Rural Microloan Revolving Loan Fund. This fund will help 10 small businesses which will help create 10 and save 10 rural jobs.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to further communication with the purchase of BK Commander Radios. The BK radios will provide radio coverage for the entire district including all the river gorges and gulches. The district will also purchase new MSA gas meter monitors for the firefighter to use as needed. The district will invest in hose acquisition and recovery parts. Lastly, the district will purchase truck rescue struts. The struts are safety equipment used in stabilizing the rescue crews and vehicles during cliff rescues or vehicle extractions. This is all needed and will benefit the community of Albion as it sits along the infamous curvy Highway 1 in Mendocino County.

borrower_name: FRIENDS OF THE ROUND VALLEY PUBLIC LIBRA
funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Information (51)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to purchase an air purifier for the Friends of the Round Valley Public Librarys community room and technical equipment for Round Valley Library Commons. This will allow Friends to continue providing essential services to the town of Covelo and the surrounding community while at the same time continuing to follow the Centers for Disease Control and Preventions, state, and county guidance for indoor services in a safe manner.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide Elk Fire Department with much needed multi-band radios. Their current radios are outdated and do not allow them to communicate with other fire departments in emergency situations. With wildfires being a constant threat to the area, these radios could be the difference in an emergency. Elk Community Services district is a 57-square-mile area. This is a heavily wooded area and clear communication is key to keep everyone safe from the threat of fire.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a much-needed backhoe that will be used during emergency situations such as moving down trees, and other essential emergency services

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a new playground for the Pacific Community Charter School. The new playground facilities will improve the wellness of both students at teachers at the school, allowing space for students to destress and recharge outside of the learning environment. Having the playground will also encourage parents to enroll their childern in the school and enhance community cohesion and well-being.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a much-needed type III engine that will be used to combat fires in an area where fires have increased dramatically over the years. The new type III engine will provide a safer environment for firefighters to work in.

funding_code: RRH-NONSUBSIDIZED-SEC538 GUARANTEED
naics_industry_sector: Real Estate and Rental and Leasing (53)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development loan guarantee will be used to assist in the acquisition and rehabilitation ofWalnut Apartments, an existing Section 515 multi-family housing complex in Fort Bragg, California. The project will go through significant rehabilitation and improve the living conditions for all the current and future tenants. The property consists of seven two-story garden-style residential apartment buildings containing 24 one-bedroom, 28 two-bedroom, and four three-bedroom units. Common amenities include a leasing office and laundry room.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a fire truck for the city of Alturas volunteer fire department. Located in Modoc County, the city of Alturass fire department is staffed by 36 volunteers that provide fire suppression and protection services for a 2.45 square mile catchment area. Additionally, the department has a mutual aid agreement with the Alturas Rural Fire Department to assist with fires within a nine-mile radius of the city. The department also has agreements with Alturas Rancheria, XL Reservation, and the Modoc National Wildlife Refuge. The Alturas Fire Department will purchase a 2021 Rosenbauer Timberwolf Urban Interface Pumper to replace an older pumper purchased in 1985. Having a working, modern fire truck is crucial to the rural citys safety and allows the department to maintain its Insurance Organization rating which maintains affordable insurance rates for the towns residents.

funding_code: DISTANCE LEARNING- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to establish a distance learning system to connect residents in the towns of Shafter and Lost Hills with Bakersfield College. The school will build in each town state-of-the-art classrooms equipped with interactive televisions and computers with internet access. The videoconferencing technology will enable courses to be streamed from the colleges main campus in Bakersfield, from the Delano campus, and from the Wasco Adult Education Center. Course offerings will include health care, industrial automation and classes in Science, Technology, Engineering and Math (STEM) This project is expected to provide a skilled workforce for in-demand jobs in the health care and automation industries in high-poverty rural areas of Kern County.

funding_code: DISTANCE LEARNING- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase equipment to be used to implement a centralized remote distance learning model for California Rural Water Association to teach students participating in an Apprenticeship Program in four different locations in California. The end-user sites are in the city of Corning, city of Montague, Golden Hills Community Services District, and Lake County Special Districts and will benefit approximately 28,000 residents. The program provides a pathway for employed utility workers to upgrade and enhance their Technical, Managerial, and Financial understanding and skills in the operation and management of their local utilities.

funding_code: TELEMEDICINE- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to establish a telemedicine system linking San Ysidro Healths eight health care clinics in San Diego County to two end-user sites in rural eastern San Diego County. The services will include treatment of substance use disorders; primary medical care; pediatric and womens health care; specialty medical care, including cardiology and HIV primary care; health education; and family planning.

funding_code: TELEMEDICINE- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to connect the Visalia hospital, General Medical Education, and Kaweah Health Mental Hospital with Exeter, Woodlake and Lindsay clinics and patients across Tulare county in California. Using a robust telehealth and updated communications network, this project will focus on treating those with substance and opioid use disorders, as well as other chronic diseases and general health issues can be treated with telehealth visits. The project will connect 40 doctors, including specialists with 200,000 people in Tulare county.

funding_code: DLT GRANTS - CARES ACT - EDUCATIONAL
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to establish distance learning services to expand Science, Technology, Engineering and Math (STEM)-based courses and activities at four rural high schools in the Central Valley. Courses will include dual-credit courses provided by Merced College and high school courses including Advanced Placement, core and elective courses.

funding_code: TELEMEDICINE- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide equipment for distance learning Science, Technology, Engineering and Math (STEM) courses and career counseling in Napa, Sonoma and Santa Cruz counties. This project will link Pacific Union College to three rural high schools. The project also will connect students and residents in and around Rio Lindo Adventist Academy in Healdsburg with students and residents in and around Monterey Bay Academy in La Selva Beach.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to resolve the issue that the city of Newcastle has been dealing with over the last couple of years in their 100-year-old fire station. The Newcastle Fire Protection District (NFPD) has been dealing with a building that has been structurally falling apart. NFPD has repaired the sagging front wall, with shoring posts and the installed new steel beams and concrete to shore up the west side of the building. After the last repair, the county deemed that the building would need to be replaced with a new modern fire station, as the 100-year-old building would be too far beyond repair to safely house the fire department employees. The Newcastle Fire Protection District proposes to construct a new fire station on vacant land donated to the fire district that is centrally located in the districts jurisdiction. The new 6,500 square foot building will have an apparatus room of 4,000 square feet and 2,500 square feet of living and office space. The apparatus room will be a metal building and roof with sheet rock on the interior. The living and office area will be Type V wood construction with a metal roof, stucco exterior and sealed concrete floors.The District has already completed extensive site preparation including the required environmental, geological and impact reports, the District will contribute $978,357 total towards the project. The District, through a formal bidding process has accepted the lowest responsible bidder to construct the station.The project will ensure the residents of the city of Newcastle and surrounding Communities will have a safe new Fire Station with modern equipment to serve them in case of a fire event or medical emergency.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) 306C-NATIVE AMERICAN-WASTE ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to install approximately 4,100 feet of eigh inch PVC sewer main and install manholes along Monroe Street near the Torres-Martinez Desert Cahuilla Indian Reservation in southwestern Riverside County. The new eight inch sewer main will be connected to an existing 33-inch sewer main, owned and operated by the Coachella Valley Water District (CVWD). The new sewer main will connect a subdivision, church, and community building located within the Torres-Martinez Desert Cahuilla Indian Reservation to the existing sewer collection system operated by CVWD. The housing units and facilities that will connect to the new sewer main currently discharge sewage into septic tanks located on each property. The Torres-Martinez Desert Cahuilla Indian tribe has determined that these tanks are failing and have caused seepage of sewage to ground water and in cases sewage has been detected above ground. The proposed project will allow the Tribe to abandon the failing septic tanks and allow them to connect to CVWDs existing sewage treatment system.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to resolve a water truck issue that Sierra County has been dealing with over the last couple of years. The Sierra County Roads & Transportation Department were reviewing their needs during this current fire season, they realized there was a need for a water truck on the eastern side of the county, since the only water truck currently was 80 miles to the west, after experiencing a major fire in 2020 near the city of Loyalton and the proximity of the current Dixie fire. The Sierra County project consists of the purchase of a water truck with 4,000-gallon capacity, sprayers, and equipped with a water cannon. The new water truck will allow Sierra County to cover the eastern side of the county, while their other water truck is stationed on the western side of the county. This will enable the county to have sufficient water supply for water demand during a fire event.The project will ensure the residents of Eastern Sierra County that a water truck will be in the area in case of a fire event. They will no longer need to wait for the current water truck to arrive - which is 80 miles away.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to resolve an operational deficiency in the squad cars that Sierra County has been dealing with for years. The Sierra County Law Enforcement Department has recognized their need to correct their inefficient in-car communication system, also known as the Race Elimination Profile Act, and the need for two new all-wheel drive squad cars. Currently, they must travel 20+ miles back to the station to input the required race and gender identifying information, after an incident or arrest. The lack of mobile communication puts officers lives at risk. The Sierra County project consists of the purchase of two new Ford Explorer cars and Mobile Data Terminal Computers. All current vehicles will be equipped as well, which will allow significant improvements across the board for the agency. The new equipment will allow the department to perform all records-management, inputting of data during service requests or on patrol throughout the county. This will enable the department to improve data integrity during their officers shifts and give the department the ability to directly communicate or interact with the officers while they are in the field. The officers will no longer need to travel back to the hub, some 20-plus miles to complete reports, which will improve the safety of the officer. The new equipment and patrol vehicles will be a welcomed improvement for the residents living or traveling in Sierra County

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to resolve a fire flow issue that Sierra County Waterworks District No. 1-Calpine has been dealing with over the last couple of years. The Calpine Water System were cited for violating the Health and Safety Code on March 4, 2015 (Arsenic issues, which is resolved), but now are faced with inadequate water flow during a fire, which resulted in four homes being burned down over the last couple of years. The Calpine Water System Improvement project consists of Construction of a New Water Tank with 140,000-gallon capacity, new piping, inlets and outlets, erosion control, foundation building, and site restoration. The new water tank will allow SCWWD No. 1 to take down their other Water Tank and do needed maintenance, as well as enable the District to have sufficient water supply for daily water demand, fire storage and the possibility of expansion.The project will not only ensure safe, clean drinking water is provided to all residents of the Big Bend service area, but the insurance of extra water flow during a fire event.

project_name: Main Street Sewer Interceptor Improvement Project
funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to replace aging infrastructure, reduce inflow & infiltration, provide adequate hydraulic capacity, and ensure safe and reliable transmission of wastewater to the Citys wastewater treatment plant. The proposed project includes improvements to the Citys sewer collection system within the Caltrans road right-of-way (ROW) along Highway 3 (Main Street) between Lennox Road and Oberlin Road. Improvements include replacement of 1,500 feet of 15-inch sewer mains with 18-inch sewer mains; 2,100 feet of 18-inch sewer main with a 21-inch sewer main; rehabilitation with cured-in-place pipe of 300 feet of 21-inch, 1,000 feet of 18-inch, and 2,400 feet of 15-inch sewer mains; abandonment of 8,300 feet of sewer mains and 35 manholes, installation of 17 manholes; replacement of 9 manholes; and replacement of 120 sewer laterals.

naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
naics_description: FRUIT AND TREE NUT COMBINATION FARMING
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a 1.0mW solar array to offset electrical costs incurred by normal business operations. TriNut Farm Management Inc. is a medium size family farm growing almond trees which produce supports affiliated industry involved in almond processing then sold to the marketplace. Project funds will be used for the purchase of a 508kW solar array to offset electrical costs incurred by normal business operations. This project will realize $239,820 per year in savings, and will replace 1,142,000 kWh per year, which is enough electricity to power 93.2 homes per year.

funding_code: GUARANTEED B&I 3% FEE LOAN
naics_industry_sector: Accommodation and Food Services (72)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investmentwill be used to purchase of a 82-room Best Western Plus branded lodging facility located at Patterson, CA. Patterson is known as the" Apricot Capital of the World." The town holds an annual Apricot Fiesta and other events. Hotel accommodations are needed to house visitors and travelers. Additionally, this fund will help save 18 existing rural jobs and improve the local economy.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to ensure all firefighters have the access to properly functioning equipment to keep them safe while they keep the community safe. They currently have 12 Self-Contained Breathing Apparatus (SCBA) units that need to be replaced immediately. Each is over 10 years old and not in the best condition. The district is running the risk of not having functioning SCBA in the next couple years. The district had 40 fire responses last year which would be an issue if they no longer have functioning respiratory protection. These grant funds will pay for 12 full sets of SCBA equipment, one large cylinder, and a Rapid Intervention Team bag.

project_name: POLICE VEHICLES AND A CITY VEH
funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to replace five police patrol vehicles and a public works vehicle. The five new vehicles will be Ford Interceptor hybrid vehicles with uplift packages and one public works. The vehicles will service the entire city of Woodlake and may also respond to calls in the nearby unincorporated area. The city relies on patrol vehicles to respond to calls and provide public service. The vehicles being replaced are at the end of their useful operating life and the city lacks funding to replace these vehicles without grant assistance. The city has been able to obtain a grant from San Joaquin Valley Air Pollution Control District to upgrade to low-emission vehicles, which will cover a portion of the matching funds.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
naics_description: COMMERCIAL AND INDUSTRIAL MACHINERY AND EQUIPMENT (EXCEPT AUTOMOTIVE AND ELECTRONIC) REPAIR AND MAINTENANCE
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a walk-in freezer for the cafeteria at Columbia Elementary School. The purchase of the walk-in freezer will allow for replacement of the current freezer which has limited capacity (is freestanding) and is non-functioning (will not hold Freon and has a failed seal). The current freezer is over 10 years old and does not allow for the safe storage of student meal products. The new walk-in freezer will ensure the elementary students are receiving healthy and safe meals.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and outfit a fully equipped law enfrocement vehicle that will be used in the rural community of Sonora. The purchase of the vehicle will allow older, unsafe vehicles to be rotated out of the Sonora Department vehicle fleet. Sonora Departments calls for service have increased every year from 13,699 in 2018 to 16,348 in 2019, and over 19,260 in 2020. The dramatic increase in calls is due to increased homelessness, opioid use, and a crisis of abuse. The new patrol vehicle will allow the department to respond safely and quickly to calls for service.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and outfit a fully equipped law enfrocement vehicle that will be used in the rural community of Sonora. The purchase of the vehicle will allow older, unsafe vehicles to be rotated out of the Sonora Department vehicle fleet. funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: The Rural Development investment will be used to rehabilitate the parking lot at the Tuolumne County Superintendent of Schools office and make changes to ensure the parking lot meets current accessibility requirements under the Americans with Disabilities Act. This office serves the entire county of Tuolumne.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Transportation and Warehousing (48-49)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a van to support education in Toulumne County. The van will serve the countys 12 school districts and the office of the Superintendent of Toulumne County Schools. Staff will be transported to provide speech, psychological, occupational, and physical therapies. Additionally, the van will be used to transport curriculum, student meals and other educational materials. Importantly, students will be transported to community college classes, community-based instruction, court school, adult education, alternative education and special education classes.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: The Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install an emergency generator at the fire station and purchase much needed rescue and fire fighter equipment including: Hurst Tool (similar to Jaws of Life), breathing apparatus sets, extra breathing apparatus bottles, personal protective equipment, and rope rescue pack. The fire station has been without power for up to five days due to Public Safety Power Shutoff events, making it impossible for the fire fighters to refill air tanks for breathing apparatus and to open the door to get the fire engine out of the station. The rescue equipment to be purchased will allow the fire department to safely perform rescues to people in accidents and fires. The breathing apparatus and personal protective equipment will allow fire fighters safety during incidents. Fire fighting service is a critical community service provided by this public body in this remote part of Tuolumne County.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: The Rural Development investment will be used to replace the heating ventilation and air conditioning (HVAC) units at the Tuolumne County Superintendent of Schools main office. The current HVAC has failed leaving the public, students and employees without proper ventilation, air conditioning and heating. This office serves the entire county of Tuolumne.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to for make renovations the Sonora Regional Wastewater Treatment Facility. Deficiencies will be addressed by making improvements to each unit process: Secondary Treatment, Disinfection, Sludge Stabilization and Drying, and Sludge De-watering. This will allow the system to increase the treatment capacity - including full nitrification/denitrification, handle variable flow and load including septage, and improve the effluent quality to ensure regulatory compliance.

funding_code: MAND. RENEW ENERFY SYSTEMS GRANTS UNDER $20,000
naics_industry_sector: Retail Trade (44-45)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist Capay Valley Growers Incorporated purchase a 30 kilowatt (kW) solar array to offset electrical costs incurred by normal operations. This project will save $11,223 per year and replace 44,780 watt hours per year, which is enough electricity to power three homes per year.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: MAND. RENEW ENERFY SYSTEMS GRANTS UNDER $20,000
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
naics_description: OTHER VEGETABLE (EXCEPT POTATO) AND MELON FARMING
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help farmers, ranchers, and rural small businesses develop renewable energy systems, and make energy-efficiency improvements. Robert Hines, dba Sun Tracker Farms, is family-owned small, CCOF organic, diversified farm in rural Capay Valley town of Guinda, Cali. High energy cost compromise a large part of the farms operating expenses. Project funds will be used for the purchase of a 13kW solar array to offset electrical costs incurred by normal operations. This project will save $5,072 per year and will replace 22050kWh per year, which is enough electricity to power 1.8 homes per year.

funding_code: (WWA PROGRAM AREA) SOLID WASTE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide hands-on solid waste and resilience planning and management through technical assistance and training. The project will provide direct and indirect assistance to 26 California, six Arizona, 13 Nevada and four New Mexico federally-recognized tribes to reduce their solid waste streams, divert waste from the landfills, reduce water and climate pollution, and build Tribal resilience. The project will accomplish this task by providing one-on-one direct consultations, workshops and technical assistance materials with rural and remote Tribes and Tribal solid waste managers.

funding_code: (WWA PROGRAM AREA) TAT GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance and training to underserved communities in the United States Commonwealth of Puerto Rico that fall outside of their water utility. The utility, called the Puerto Rico Aqueduct and Sewer Authority (PRASA), owns and operates Puerto Ricos public water supply and wastewater systems. Earth Island Institute will provide training to those small water systems outside of the PRASA known as non-PRASA water systems to assist them in building their organizational capacity to improve the effectiveness and efficiency of the water facilities.

project_name: Kirkwood Meadows PUD Wastewater Treatment Plant Improvements
funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to complete improvements to the districts wastewater treatment plant. The proposed improvements consist of replacement and refurbishment of essential equipment for the Membrane Bioreactor wastewater treatment system as well as upgrades to the wastewater plant building structure. The applicant is a small utility district that primarily serves a small rural residential community and seasonal commercial customers. The district has been burdened with recent events, including the COVID-19 pandemic and the Caldor Wildfire, that impacted the districts wastewater operations. The proposed project will be completed within the boundaries of the wastewater treatment facility. Completion of the project will allow the district to replace plant components that are well past their useful operating life and improve their wastewater treatment during peak flow conditions.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE NATIVE AMERICAN GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to deliver training and technical assistance to multiple tribes within California. The State of California Tribal Microenterprise Development provides training and technical assistance in microenterprise and small business skills development to rural Native entrepreneurs living in California, especially those living on reservations. The center will work with the following California Tribes: Big Pine Paiute, Bishop Paiute, Coyote Valley Band of Pomo Indians, Tolowa Dee-ni Nation, Torres Martinez Desert Cahuilla Indians, Washoe Tribe of Nevada and California, Wiyot, and Yorok.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide direct marketing technical assistance to microenterprise businesses located in rural communities that meet the income threshold designated by the Community Services Block Grant Act in the counties of Butte, Glenn, Colusa, Tehama, Shasta, and Lassen, Calif. Over 20 small businesses will benefit from this project.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide a feasibility study. This grant will support the costs associated with the preparation of an economically-driven feasibility study of the infrastructure and development costs for commercial expansion and business opportunities along Interstate 5 in the Northern California Cities of Orland and Coring. The project will help at least one small business in this rural area.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Information (51)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an emergency generator and broadcasting equipment for Golden Valley Community Broadcasters. The new generator is necessary to allow the continued Emergency Management System broadcasts and emergency instructions in the event of disasters such as the Camp Fire in 2018. During the Camp Fire and during Californias frequent public safety power shutoffs, the emergency broadcasting capabilities of community radio station KZFR are in danger of being blacked out. In a region where many residents do not have cell phones or access to the internet, radio is the only reliable source of emergency information available to them. In a wildfire situation, prompt and accurate evacuation instructions are vital as conditions change rapidly and ingress and egress to and from the communities are extremely limited, often confined to one or two main roads.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide mobile literacy services and traditional and digital bookmobile services to residents of outlying areas of Butte County, especially those impacted by the 2018 Camp Fire and those lacking public or private transportation. The proposed vehicle will consist of a 36-foot plugin hybrid bookmobile that will include: a wheelchair lift, skylights, awning, video surveillance, public speaking system, a robust satellite facilitated Wi-Fi cellular hotspot and modular conversion system which will provide flexibility to operate as a mobile library but also as a classroom and story area. Due to COVID, the project was delayed and had cost overruns, necessitating a subsequent grant of $56,100 to ensure project completion.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will allow the town of Paradises law enforcement agency to purchase a new model, heavy duty pickup truck that will include an animal control kennel body. Due to the terrain traversed, the new vehicle must be four-wheel drive. Additionally, it will have five separate air-conditioned kennels, a hydraulic dead animal carrier, separate compartment for tools and equipment, safety warning lights, full factory towing package, a multi-band mobile radio and mobile data computer. The town provides animal control services through the Paradise Police Department Animal Control and Shelter.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a street sweeper and a Community Services Officer truck for the town of Paradise. A camp fire destroyed vegetation throughout the town and now debris from rain runs off and accumulates on the roads. This creates hazardous road conditions and may impact streams and wildlife. The street sweeper will allow the town to clear debris, creating a safer environment. In addition, the town of Paradise Law Enforcement Department provides evidence and property processing via a Community Services Officer (CSO). The CSO truck will enable timely processing as well as transport and towing of larger evidence items.

borrower_name: BOYS & GIRLS CLUBS OF THE NORTH VALLEY
funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase program supplies and commercial heavy-duty furniture to equip the facility in Paradise, California after a recent remodel. Purchases include furniture items: seating and lounge chairs; tables and desks, and SMART screens for virtual activities. Over the last year Boys and Girls Clubs of North Valley (BGCNV) have emphasized the need for access to virtual learning and need SMART screens to make much of their program possible. IT equipment and supplies will need to be purchased along with a copier to have on site to support programing, front desk, and the site coordinator. These purchases will include the initial cost of the technology and equipment along with software and setup fees. BGCNV intend to purchase a 10-seat passenger van and a minivan. Club vans support not only transportation for students but access to and from their programs, field trips, and workforce development opportunities. Vans are also utilized to bring staff to their sites daily and be used in case of an emergency. Transportation is a priority, especially after the fires the town has faced.

project_name: FY22 CF GRANT TO PURCHASE CODE
funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment investment will be ued to purchase up to three new model, light duty pickups for the Code Enforcement Division. They will be 4WD, factory equipped with electrical and equipment packages designed for public safety equipment, including work lights and safety warning lights to the front, side and rear. The Town of Paradise Community Development Department provides necessary Code Enforcement services to keep the community safe through the regular inspection and follow up of critical codes and standards such as defensible space requirements on private property. The Camp Fire has caused a tremendous workload on this division with increases in utility work, recovery projects and private redevelopment. The Department is hiring additional staff to support these efforts and currently does not have appropriate vehicles for their primary job function.

All units will go through significant rehabilitation and improve the living conditions for all current and future tenants.

naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a refrigerator and freezer and to hire two full-time medical assistants necessary to help at-risk, farm worker and migrant families obtain food, medical treatment, and access to COVID-19 vaccinations and testing in Coalinga, Huron City, and the surrounding areas. The equipment and staff will help Westside Family Preservation Services Network provide a needed service to an at-risk community, many of whom are nutritionally compromised, lack transportation to seek health treatment and testing and lack the resources to seek help outside their encampments.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase six hybrid vehicles, telehealth computers, food bags, a refrigerator, and a freezer necessary to help at-risk, farm worker and migrant families obtain food, medical treatment, and access to COVID-19 vaccinations and testing in Huron City, and the surrounding areas. The equipment will help Westside Family Preservation Services Network provide a needed service to an at-risk community, many of whom are nutritionally compromised, lack transportation to seek health treatment and testing and lack the resources to seek help outside of their encampments.

The purchase of additional water allowed the city to meet its water demands.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help with technical assistance and training programs to small businesses in eligible rural areas of San Joaquin County, Calif. The activities will generate useful information and facilitate business development in several persistent poverty Counties. At least 20 small and mid-sized businesses will be benefited from these training programs. The funds will help at create three and save seven rural jobs and will bring economic sustainability in these rural areas.

naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined

The service area includes the Counties of Fresno, Kern, Kings, Madera, Merced, San Joaquin, Fresno, Stanislaus and Tulare. This will benefits 25 small businesses and will will help create 48 and save 12 rural jobs.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: MAND. RENEW ENERFY SYSTEMS GRANTS UNDER $20,000
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Jennifer Simone purchase a 23.7 kW solar photovoltaic system. Jennifer Simone is a sole proprietor farmer growing almond trees and producing almonds for processing through area hulling operations and then for sale. This project will realize $9,050 per year in savings, and will replace 36,200 kW per year, which is enough electricity to power 3.2 homes per year.

funding_code: DISCRETION RURAL MICROPENTERPR DEV ORG
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to rural micro-entrepreneurs and microenterprises that have received or are seeking one or more microloans from the micro lender. This includes marketing, management, and other forms of technical assistance needed in Fresno and surrounding counties. The funds will help at least 10 rural businesses, help create 10 jobs, and save 10 rural jobs.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY AGRICULTURAL PRODUCT MARKET DEVELOPMENT GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
naics_description: OTHER VEGETABLE (EXCEPT POTATO) AND MELON FARMING
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist Balakian Farms with processing and supplies for their Organic Bread and Butter Pickles product. Located in Fresno County, Balakian Farms is an independent family-owned farm that produces organic produce and manufactures value-added products and sell direct-to-consumer, wholesale and retail. As a result, an anticipated expansion in customer base of 3,500 is expected. One job will be created.

borrower_name: CENTER FOR FAMILY HEALTH & EDUCATION, INC
funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an electronic healthcare records system for Center for Family Health & Education Inc. (CFFHE) in Orange Cove. CFFHE provides the local rural community with quality healthcare, with an emphasis on underserved communities. CFFHE is a not-for-profit organization formed in April 2009, with an objective to promote physical and mental health, and health education to the community, regardless of their ability to pay. This system has a strong focus on patient engagement and facilitating remote care with numerous telehealth options, from supporting video visits and post-surgical follow-ups to patient monitoring features. The need for this system has greatly increased due to the conditions arising from the COVID-19 pandemic.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: The Rural Development investment will be used to purchase food and equipment for food distribution and increase food storage capacity, in three rural communities. This project will also support Central California Food Banks newly-created food pantries and neighborhood market programs to meet the increasing demand for food distribution service in the aftermath of COVID-19 pandemic, serving the communities of Caruthers, Lemon Cove, and Springville.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: The Rural Development investment will be used to purchase food and equipment for rural food distribution programs and to increase food storage capacity, in 16 rural communities. This project will support Central California Food Bank newly-created food pantries and neighborhood market programs to meet the increasing demand for food distribution service in the aftermath of COVID-19 pandemic. More than 20 percent of the population in most of the project service areas are living below poverty level. The communities served are Allensworth, Alpaugh, Biola, Cantua Creek, Coarsegold, Goshen, Ivanhoe, Oakhurst, Pixley, Poplar, Raisin City, Richgrove, San Joaquin, Strathmore, Tranquility, and Traver.
