program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist Fiack Family Farms offset the costs associated with installing a photovoltaic solar system. Fiack Family Farms is an agriculture producer growing rice crops in Glenn County, California. This project will realize $20,146 per year in savings, and the system projects to generate 62,159 kilowatt hours (kWh) per year, which is enough electricity to power five homes per year.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will allow the Willows Fire Rural Fire District to purchase a desperately needed firetruck. The quick attack truck will provide critical wildland access in their district.The Willows Rural Fire Protection district has no paid staff and relies upon dedicated volunteers to staff and respond to calls. The Willows Rural Fire Protection District serves an area that spans roughly 78-square miles.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a flatbed truck, a dump truck, two ATVs, and a backhoe. The new equipment will allow Willows Fire and Public Works departments to replace aged equipment and ensure better response to fire and flood risks for residents as well as to maintain flood control infrastructure.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a Type 3 wildland fire truck to replace a fire engine that is more than 25 years old. The truck will become the districts main wildland response vehicle, providing quick fire suppression and medical care. Quick fire suppression is vital to the area, as it is very dry with tall grass and heavy brush. Knocking down fires and providing rapid medical care is critical to the health and safety of area residents, and the state through the districts involvement with Cal Fire activities. Existing equipment is no longer mechanically dependable, nor is it efficient or safe for firefighter transportation. While the Elk Creek Fire Protection District has worked diligently to be fiscally conservative and continuously save for critical purchases, without the USDA s Community Facilities program, the equipment fund would be depleted, leaving no funds for potential emergency needs.

project_name: FY22 CF GRANT- PURCHASE VHF PA
funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase up to 104 very high frequency pagers to be issued to individuals in order to notify first responders of emergency calls. On January 1, 2023, this will be the only practical way that notifications will be made. These emergency pagers will equip volunteer firefighters with the necessary emergency paging equipment to reduce response times, increasing the departments ability to protect life, property, and environment through quick suppression of fires, reducing greenhouse gases. The pagers will help fire fighters protect and serve the district which includes a large portion of the Mendocino National Forest, Grindstone Rancheria (tribal lands) and significant critical infrastructure.

project_name: FY22 CF GRANT- PURCHASE ATV, P
funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a fire mechanic service vehicle, an all-terrain vehicle, and a towable utility pump for the Orland Fire Department. The utility terrain vehicle will enable fire suppression activities in the Stony Creek area north of town which is prone to seasonal fires but inaccessible to fire engines and trucks. The fire mechanic service vehicle will ensure immediate repair response so that equipment needed for firefighting is quickly returned to service.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist the Orland Fire Department (OFD) to purchase a desperately needed water tender that will provide a reliable water supply to their firefighting fleet in remote areas. The water tender with a 4,000-gallon tank will allow the department to have a critical water supply for fire suppression in their area of operations and within nine other mutual aid departments. The ability to get water to the fire safely will enable the OFD to knock down the fire quickly, save lives, preserve property and help to protect the firefighters, mostly composed of volunteers. The cost for a water tender is $141,608 and the citys rural counterpart, the Orland Fire Protection District, which is a separate entity, has pledged to provide the $92,108 shared cost (65 percent).

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will allow the Willows Fire Department to purchase new fire hose and nozzles that meet National Fire Protection Association standards, new personal protective equipment to outfit members for safe structural firefighting, updated radios, and thermal imaging equipment.The current inventory of these items are aged and do not meet industry standards.The City of Willows Fire Department currently provides all fire protection and emergency medical services in Willows.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a new flatbed truck, dump truck, two ATVs, and a backhoe. The flatbed truck will be used to haul assorted items, including sandbags, during flood events and equipment during fire events that require evacuations etc. The dump truck will be used to haul debris remove fire hazards, clearing out flood infrastructure and provide sand for sandbag filling stations. The ATVs will be used to navigate levees to move flood control pumps and carry supplies and firefighters during fast moving wild land urban interface fires. The backhoe will be used to dig fuel breaks and remove hazardous fuels from the Willows area as well as construct, repair, and maintain flood control infrastructure.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to remove aging septic systems and install a new waste water collection system and treatment facility. The completed project will correct this issue.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help deliver vaccines to rural communities through mobile vaccine clinics. Pioneers Memorial Healthcare Districts mobile unit travels to multiple rural cities in the county on a regular schedule, providing screenings and treatment for people at risk of COVID-19 and other chronic health conditions. The unit also provides medication management, eye and dental care, immunizations, facilitation of telemedicine consultations with specialists, and other healthcare services. This mobile clinic is a self-contained unit and will help deliver services in geographically isolated areas or small towns that may lack access to healthcare providers and COVID-19 immunizations and treatments.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase 200 iPads and Chromebooks, and security cameras. The iPads will enhance learning for the Transitional Kindergarten and Kindergarten students at Dogwood Elementary. The Chromebooks will replace devices at Heber Elementary. The additional cameras will be installed at both schools. They will provide coverage for access points and other areas of potential security risk to give students a safer learning environment.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install two display monitors (one classroom will get three monitors) on each of the walls of the four classrooms and purchase furniture to promote the use of smaller groups being able to use the monitors. The current classroom configuration is the traditional seating - facing the front of the classroom with a projector. With the new configuration, the classes can be assigned small groups; and those small groups can use each of the wall monitors to collaborate. The current classroom configuration for both the science and the math classrooms are out of date for the current instruction for STEAM. The need for small groups working on lab projects - collaboration assignments are hindered with old-style desks and the use of the traditional front-facing classroom. With the new wall monitors and furniture, the teacher will be able to utilize the room to help to maximize the space.

project_name: 2022 Kettleman City CSD ECWAG Water Purchase
funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) ECWAG - APPROPRIATED $1,000,000 LIMIT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase 117-acre feet of water needed by the Kettleman City Community Service District in order to meet its water demand. Funding is also provided in order to continue a Total Trihalomethanes treatment pilot study for the evaluation of additional seasonal treatment study data and for a temporary reduction of the Total Trihalomethanes surface water contaminant caused by the severe drought in California.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used tocreate and fund a system in Lake County whereby businesses have access to a one-stop shop that can help directly or refers businesses to the appropriate, experienced technical assistance to help solve problems and to find business opportunities. This fund will help directly and indirectly create 14 and save 28 jobs in this rural area.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist farmers, ranchers, and rural small businesses in developing renewable energy systems, and in making energy-efficiency improvements to their operations. Edenberry is an organic farm, growing mixed vegetables as well as raspberry and blackberries. The fund will help offset the costs associated with installing a photovoltaic (PV) solar system. The project will generate 13,504 kWh per year. The energy will be used for irrigation well pump, cold s refrigeration, fruit freezers and freeze dryer.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to hire an Infection Control Nurse (ICN) who will be responsible for the coordination of virus prevention and treatment services of COVID-related care on behalf of Mendocino Community Health Clinic, Inc. (dba Lake View Health Center), and the management of all vaccine inventory. This project will also include the purchase of two TruMed AccuVax machines, two TruMed AccuShelves, a welcome tablet for touchless patient interactions, and a generator to power them in an emergency. The clinic offers medical, dental and behavioral health services from four health clinics, two located in Ukiah, and two in Lake County, one being the Lakeview Health Center. The center houses the administrative, medical, dental and behavioral health services for the region. In addition to serving the health needs of the residents of Lakeport, Lakeview also has patients that come in from the neighboring counties.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase law enforcement vehicles that will keep the community safe and provide transportation for officers. The vehicles will be more reliable and able to respond faster to emergencies.

naics_industry_sector: Real Estate and Rental and Leasing (53)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist in the transfer, assumption and rehabilitation of Clearlake Apartments, a family multifamily housing complex in Clearlake. The project consists of 32 one-bedroom, 36 two-bedroom, and four three-bedroom units. All units will undergo significant rehabilitation and improve the living conditions for all current and future tenants.

funding_code: RRH-NONSUBSIDIZED-SEC538 GUARANTEED
naics_industry_sector: Real Estate and Rental and Leasing (53)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist in the new construction ofKelseyville Family Apartments, a family multifamily housing complex in Kelseyville. This project has a total of 18 two-bedroom, 18 three-bedroom, and 18 four-bedroom units housed in four, two-story garden-style apartment buildings. The property also includes a one-story community building containing a community room, kitchen area, business center, leasing office, and laundry room, a picnic area, playground, basketball court, and soccer field.

borrower_name: Big Valley Band of Pomo Indians of Big Valley Rancheria
funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) 306C-NATIVE AMERICAN-WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a new drinking water treatment facility. Tribal residents currently rely on an aging and unreliable drinking water treatment facility. The project will demolish the treatment plant and install a new drinking water treatment plant. The new treatment facility will provide safe and reliable drinking water to tribal residents.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase the Long Valley Charter School (LVCS), a non-profit public benefit corporation currently rents for its Thompson Peak Charter School. Long Valley Charter School operates two charter schools. Each school is recognized as a Local Education Agency (LEA) by the state of California, providing educational programs for grades K-12. The first LEA, Long Valley School, has a classroom-based campus in Doyle, California, and a resource center for independent study in Portola, California. The second LEA, Thompson Peak Charter School is located in Susanville, California, and provides an independent study-based program. The Thompson Peak facility was originally built in 1966 as a church building, and the gross building area is around 12,266-square feet. In addition to the buildings, the project site also has an asphalt paved parking area and limited landscaping associated with the property. LVCS will be contributing their own funds to bring the building into compliance with the current accessibility standards. These improvements will be completed within one year of the loan closing.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist farmers, ranchers, and rural small businesses in developing renewable energy systems, and in making energy-efficiency improvements to their operations. Gina Covina is a sole proprietor farmer growing and marketing over 200 variety of seeds under the business name as Open Circle Seeds. High-energy cost comprises a large part of the business operating expenses. These funds will be used for the purchase and installation of a solar array which will generate 21,757 kWh per year to offset electrical costs incurred by normal operations. This project will realize $9,120 per year in savings.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants

naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help offset the costs associated with installing a photovoltaic solar system. Thurston Auto Plaza Inc. is a rural small auto retail facility in Mendocino County, California. This project will realize $40,517 per year in savings, and the system projects to generate 282,696 kilowatt hours (kWh) per year, which is enough electricity to power 26 homes per year.

funding_code: DISCRETION RURAL MICROPENTERPR DEV ORG
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to microentrepreneurs and microenterprises that are located within the Micro Development Organizations (MDOs) service area. Technical assistance will be available to applicants, potential applicants and existing borrowers that have received loans from the MDO under their Rural Microloan Revolving Loan Fund. This fund will help 10 small businesses which will help create 10 and save 10 rural jobs.

funding_code: VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER DVLP GRANTS-DISCR
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist a farmer that is located in Mendocino County, California. Boonville Barn Collective LLC will use funds to pay for value-added processing and supplies of dried pepper products. As a result, an increase of 539 baseline customers is expected. These funds will help create at least two rural jobs.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to facilitate Mendocino Community Health Clinic, Inc. [MCHC (Little Lake HC)] to hire an infection control nurse who will be responsible for the coordination of virus prevention and treatment services of COVID-related care on behalf of MCHC, and the management of all vaccine inventory. This project will also include the purchase of a TruMed AccuVax machine, a TruMed AccuShelf, welcome tablets for touchless patient interactions, and a generator to power them in an emergency. MCHC offers medical, dental and behavioral health services from four health clinics, two located in Ukiah and two in Lake County, one being the Little Lake Health Center. The Little Lake Clinic houses the administrative, medical, dental, and behavioral health services for the region. In addition to serving the health needs of the residents of Willits, Little Lake also has patients that come in from the neighboring counties.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to address COVID-19-related healthcare delivery challenges that Anderson Valley Health Center Inc. has struggled with since March 2020. The project will ensure the residents of Boonville, Mendocino County, will have a clinic prepared to care for its community, equipped to safeguard COVID-19 vaccines and manage other symptoms of the virus efficiently with less risk of health concerns related to the virus

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase the equipment and to fund staff wages needed to help with COVID-19 patients and operate a mobile health clinic. This project will include wages for a licensed vocational nurse, two medical assistants, health educator, and driver. Equipment will include the mobile clinic, refrigerator truck, portable equipment, and generator. The equipment will help Adventists Health enhance their COVID-19 vaccine/ testing capabilities in underserved areas. Adventist Health System-West (AHS-W) primarily serves rural communities, and its service area encompasses approximately 680 square miles and extends about 70 miles south from the Humboldt/Mendocino County line. AHS-W is the only hospital readily available to the residents of Fort Bragg and the Mendocino Coast.

borrower_name: CANCER RESOURCE CENTERS OF MENDOCINO COUNTY
funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase equipment and a vehicle needed to help with high-risk cancer patients seeking treatment and testing for COVID-19. This project will include a transport vehicle, telehealth iPads, mobile hotspot, and a telehealth computer. The equipment will help Cancer Resource Centers provide a needed service to an at-risk community, many of whom are immunocompromised and feel insecure seeking treatment and testing in the general population.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide staff salaries for personnel administering COVID-19 testing, for computer and software to input data from testing, and for staffing to administer testing. COVID-19 testing will focus on engagement and facilitating remote care that will help broaden testing access to support long-term sustainability of rural health care in Mendocino County.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used for telehealth services, food distribution and COVID-19 testing. Mendocino Coast Hospitality Center (MCHC) provides the local rural community with homeless shelters that provide a safe place to sleep, services and resources for people without homes. This includes transitional housing, food distribution, shelter beds, meals, laundry services, and showers year-round. MCHC is a not-for-profit organization formed in 1986, with a current objective to provide free meals, emergency shelter and services to those in need. Due to the COVID-19 epidemic, the need has increased; resources have been strained. These items will allow a strong focus on client engagement and facilitating telehealth with video visits with primary care providers, mental health professionals or specialists. The new appliances will support meal preparation. This grant will benefit 1,452 people.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to expand COVID-19 testing and vaccinations to people with developmental disabilities and to staff of Parents and Friends, Inc. This project will also assist with COVID-19 testing, coordinating tests, test tracking, and vehicles to take clients to vaccination appointments. Weekly testing and vaccinations as recommended, will allow the people with developmental disabilities to participate and reside in the programs that Parents and Friends, Inc. provide within CDC guidelines, keeping clients and staff as safe as possible.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to address issues that Mendocino Community Health Center (MCHC) Inc. has dealt with since March 2020, related to the COVID-19 pandemic. This project will help MCHC hire an infectious nurse and procure contactless machines to check people in for their appointments and machines to store the vaccine. The project will ensure the residents of Ukiah, Mendocino County, will have a clinic equipped to store their COVID-19 vaccines and efficiently care for patients with other symptoms of the virus, and with less risk of health concerns that come with the virus.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to resolve issues due to COVID-19 that Mendocino Community Health Center Inc. (MCHC) has dealt with since March 2020. This project will fund a salary for an infectious health nurse and procurement of contactless machines to check in people for their appointments and machines to house the vaccine. A generator was also needed due to the shutdowns from their electricity provider. The project will ensure the residents of Ukiah, Mendocino County, will have a clinic that will properly store its COVID-19 vaccines and efficiently care for those with symptoms of the virus, and with less risk of health concerns that come with the virus.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist the law enforcements office to purchase two special service rural patrol vehicles. The county was established in 1874 and the law enforcement office is responsible for patrolling 4,200 square miles. The county has a population of approximately 10,000 people in thirteen (13) separate townships. The office is also responsible for patrolling the countys public lands which is almost 70 percent of the county, and four Native American Reservations. The office currently has eight full time patrol deputies and two sergeants and one reserve deputy. Each officer is assigned a take home patrol unit to reduce response times. The office currently has four explorers and six pickups. Over half of the patrol vehicles have over 100,000 miles and two of the vehicles 200,000 miles, while three are almost to the 200,000 mark. The purchase of the new vehicles will not only provide more dependable respond times for emergencies, but also save money in maintenance costs.

naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund a cost overrun for the construction of a skilled nursing facility (SNF) on an approximately three-acre site owned by the District and across the street from the main hospital campus. funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a skilled nursing facility (SNF) on an approximately 3.30-acre site, owned by the district and across the street from the main hospital campus. The project will help fill the gap left by the closure of the communitys only such facility a few years ago. The need for a SNF in Quincy is well established due to the aging population and the recent increased relocation trends to more rural communities in California that are expected to continue. The nearest SNFs, are at capacity and located in Portola and Chester (32 and 45 miles away, respectively) serve different areas, and are geographically separated from Quincy by mountain passes. The projects intention is to meet the growing healthcare needs of the hospitals service area, and as a mechanism to generate revenue. Increased revenue will allow the hospital to improve healthcare services and programs to the communities it serves

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a skilled nursing facility (SNF) on an approximately 3.30-acre site, owned by the district and across the street from the main hospital campus. The project will help fill the gap left by the closure of the communitys only such facility a few years ago. The need for a SNF in Quincy is well established, with its aging population and the recent relocation trends to more rural communities in California expected to continue, the need for skilled nursing facilities will only increase. A SNF being re-established in town will allow community members to receive support in the area. The nearest SNFs, are at capacity and are in Portola and Chester (32 and 45 miles away, respectively) serving different service areas, geographically separated from Quincy by mountain passes. The projects intention is to meet the growing healthcare needs of the hospitals service area, and as a mechanism to generate revenue. Increased revenue will allow the hospital to improve healthcare services and programs to the communities it serves.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a skilled nursing facility on a 3.3-acre site, owned by the district and across the street from Quincys main hospital campus. The project will help fill the gap left by the closure of the communitys only similar facility. Quincys aging population and the recent relocation trends to California rural communities are expected to continue. This project will help avoid long commutes to other areas, meet local growing healthcare needs, and generate revenue to help improve community health care services and programs. The 22,507-square-foot construction will have a support services building with a wing of resident rooms. The facility concept provides a home-like environment in function and aesthetics. Breaking the rooms into pods will resemble a cabin from the streetscape. This carries through to the interior, where bedrooms share a living space, giving the building a lodge/hospitality feel. A highlight of the structure includes a central nursing station with satellite stations in each pod allowing for isolation of parts of the wing in the event of a transmissible illness. Small exterior courtyards will be utilized for residents outdoor amenities.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a 13,330 square foot single-story health clinic building, remodel its existing clinic (approximately 3,600 square feet), and to integrate the two structures into a single, improved facility in Burney, California. The joined facility will be 22,330 square feet and will include space for ambulatory medical, dental, behavioral health, outreach, pharmacy, optometry, lab, radiology, purchased/referred care, billing, and other services. This project will expand support, as a full-service ambulatory community health care facility, to serve during pandemics or epidemics. Pit River Health Services, Inc. (PRHS) is the non-profit 501(c)(3) corporation providing comprehensive health care for the Pit River Tribe, a federally recognized tribe from Burney in Shasta County. The Pit River Tribe is composed of 11 autonomous bands located in northeastern California. The tribe authorized PRHS to provide services to its members and other eligible native Americans in the tribes service area. PRHS offers comprehensive care including medical, dental, and mental health services to tribal and non-native Americans in the tribes ancestral grounds including communities in Shasta, Lassen and Modoc Counties. This project will provide additional support to a distressed and medically underserved area.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist the Fall River Valley Community Services District purchase 1) an 800-gallon vacuum-trailer, 2) a truck that can haul the vacuum trailer and heavy equipment and 3) a service/utility maintenance truck. The district currently rents a vacuum-trailer, which is not always available or reliable. The equipment will ensure the district has the ability to respond timely to maintenance issues and emergencies, which in return will cause a reduction of water loss and lower energy consumption due to unnecessary pumping.

borrower_name: FALL RIVER VALLEY FIRE PROTECTION DISTRICT
funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist the fire department with the purchase an emergency response vehicle that includes lifesaving equipment and a fire engine. The fire protection district was formed in September 2021, consolidating the Fall River Mills and McArthur Fire Protection Districts. The original districts were formed in 1938 and 1943. The McArthur census designated place (CDP) and Fall River Mills CDP have a combined population of 911. The department will be replacing their aging 2002 emergency response vehicle and their 1994 fire engine. The purchase of the new emergency response vehicle and fire engine will not only provide more dependable response for emergencies, but also save money in maintenance costs. The volunteer fire department also responds to emergencies outside of their area.

borrower_name: FALL RIVER VALLEY FIRE PROTECTION DISTRICT
funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist the fire department to purchase a fire engine. The fire protection district was formed in September 2021 - consolidating the Fall River Mills and McArthur Fire Protection Districts. The original districts were formed in 1938 and 1943. The McArthur Census designated place (CDP) and Fall River Mills CDP have a combined population of 911. The purchase of the fire engine will not only provide more dependable responses for emergencies, but also save money in maintenance costs. This engine will be housed at the McArthur station. The volunteer fire department also responds to emergencies outside of their area. California continues to experience hot, dry fire seasons; having the new engine in rural California will help ensure the safety of the citizens in McArthur and Fall River Mills.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to enhance the education for the students who attend the schools in the Sierra-Plumas Joint Unified School District, with the purchase of new educational music equipment and learning materials. The district currently provides minimal music education through not-for-profit organizations to the students as the music program ceased in 1986. The equipment will allow the district to provide sufficient education to the students and allow for the music program to re-open with the proper amount of equipment needed to thrive. The districts student populations include all of Sierra County and the Eastern part of Plumas County.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct an Education Resource Facility for Golden Eagle Charter School in Mt. Shasta. Golden Eagle Charter School is a personalized learning public charter school serving students in Grades K-12 in Siskiyou County, providing a personalized learning program and supporting parental choice in education in the context of a California standards-based education. The school has been renting several buildings in the city but is unable to accommodate the increasing student enrollments. This project will allow the school to consolidate its Mt. Shasta holdings to a single site allowing greater efficiency and managerial organization for the staff, governing board, students and parent populations. The School Resource Facility will consist of a one- story metal building with a gable design roof. The gross building area will be 34,973 square feet. The building will house 19 classrooms, a library, 22 offices, a conference room, two kitchens areas, four storage areas, two janitor rooms, two great rooms, a multi-purpose room, and 16 restrooms. Other planned improvements include an 82 space parking area, landscaping, fencing, and other minor improvements.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an ambulance to replace an aging and worn vehicle that was relied upon to respond to increasing service calls related to COVID-19. Tuolumne County Health and Human Services Agencys Groveland Ambulance Station serves the most rural areas of the county by maintaining paramedic advance life support and a variety of critical health care services related to the pandemic. The station provides coverage 24 hours a day and serves the rural communities of Groveland and Pine Mountain Lake. This project will promote vaccine administration and COVID-19 testing to support long-term sustainability of rural health care.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase two ambulances for Sonora, replacing an aging vehicle fleet that has worn out due to increased service calls from COVID-19 related medical services. The ambulance will provide service to the rural communities of Sonora City, Columbia, Jamestown, Chinese Camp, and Tuttletown. This project will promote vaccine and testing for COVID-19 to support long-term sustainability of rural health care.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install two generator systems for behavioral health, public health, and social service facilities in rural Tuolumne County to support residents health care needs related to the COVID-19 pandemic. The generator systems will provide onsite cold storage for the COVID-19 vaccines and will maintain health and human service operations related to the pandemic in the event of a power outage, including emergency access to government-funded shelter, food, clinical, and behavioral programs.

naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER PUBLIC BUILDING & IMPROVEMENT RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install a diesel-powered emergency generator to power Groveland Community Services Districts administrative building during emergencies and extended power outages. The administrative building hosts all supervisory control and data acquisitions, communication infrastructure and the purchase and installation of this equipment will ensure the district can provide timely services to the community of Groveland, even in the event of an emergency.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase Live Scan fingerprinting equipment, a transit van, truck, and vinyl cutter equipment for educational services in Tuolumne County. The van will be used for student transportation to and from the community college, community-based instruction, and to transport staff for various student services throughout the county. The truck will be used to transport curriculum, nutritional services, and other educational related items between the county office and the twelve school districts located within Tuolumne County. The Live Scan fingerprinting equipment will be used to provide fingerprinting services to staff and other individuals of the county. Lastly, the vinyl cutter will be used to allow access for all students and staff to create imaging for science, technology, engineering, arts, and math-related projects, curriculum, and signage.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help support a $33 million expansion of California Custom Processing, an almond and nut processor near Madera, California. The project will include construction, expansion, and additional financing of the facility. It will allow the company to increase processing by 30% to more than 100 million pounds of almonds annually.

program: Food Supply Chain Guaranteed Loan Program
borrower_name: ORIGO COLD MADERA PHASE II, LLC
funding_code: FOOD SUPPLY CHAIN (FSC)
naics_industry_sector: Real Estate and Rental and Leasing (53)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help offset the costs of constructing a 254,000 square foot cold storage facility as Phase II of the ORIGO Cold plant in Madera, California. ORIGO Cold Madera Phase II, LLC will lease the facility to Amond World who will provide storage to farmers and processors. The almond industry in central California produces 80 percent of the almonds in the world. The almonds are all harvested within a 3-month timeframe and require storage until they are used by processors. Approximately 600 million pounds of almonds are produced within 60 miles of the proposed facility. The facility is designed to hold approximately 50 million pounds. The climate-controlled facility will provide help address the current storage shortage and help maintain product quality. In the first phase of the expansion ORIGO Cold Madera Phase I constructed a 250,000 square foot facility for the same purpose.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a skilled nursing facility and hospital expansion in Alturas, California. Last Frontier Health Care District is a special healthcare district that is an agency of the State of California (as set forth in the California Government Code) and is operated and governed by a Board of Directors. The new skilled nursing facility will be built adjacent to the existing hospital and will include approximately 50 beds, providing long-term care services. The hospital expansion will include two hospital rooms and an outpatient infusion bay to accommodate current demand. The district provides outpatient services at its two medical clinics, one at the Alturas location and the other in Canby, California.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase equipment to support rural health care services arising from the COVID-19 emergency for the Last Frontier health care District (LFHCD) in Alturas, Modoc County, California. LFHCD operates an eight bed acute care facility, two rural health clinics, a retail pharmacy and a 50-bed skilled nursing facility. In addition, LFHCD provides outpatient services at its two medical clinics, one at the Alturas location and the other in Canby. The district also has a dental clinic at the Canby location. The need for these services has greatly increased due to the conditions arising for the COVID-19 emergency and this project will help support rural patient services.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to build a new acute care critical access hospital and skilled nursing facility. It will replace the current facilities which are over 50 years old and are no longer sufficient to meet seismic event safety regulation. The new facility will be constructed adjacent to the existing facility in Chester, California. In November 2022, the community issued a bond which received a remarkable 79 percent approval by county residents, demonstrating high community support. funding_code: (WWA PROGRAM AREA) TAT GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to provide financial support for the development of a rural communities SWS laboratory training program for water operations personnel. The project will provide intensive, hands-on laboratory training to water and wastewater disposal system operators throughout California, Arizona, Oregon, Nevada, Washington and Hawaii. The technical assistance through laboratory training will focus on communities that demonstrate the largest need based on population and median household income. The school will provide qualified wet bench laboratory training for untrained drinking water distribution samplers and Grade I - II laboratory technician candidates.

funding_code: (WWA PROGRAM AREA) TAT GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide support in the development of rural communities by providing legislated training to water operators and associated personnel to improve management and operation of water and wastewater disposal facilities. The school will provide additional training to help them better identify water problems and determine personalized solutions for the storage, treatment and distribution problems. The training will be serve small and very small operators in CA, AZ, WA and HI.

funding_code: (WWA PROGRAM AREA) TAT GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to develop an outreach center, consisting of well-trained outreach contact staff members; host Webinars with industry expert guest speakers; create a dynamic broadcast studio to offer additional virtual class opportunities in a hybrid learning environment; develop interactive classes to support the AST training program; and assist rural communities in economic recovery through more and better market opportunities by providing technical assistance through training of water districts/plants located in counties identified by the USDA as at risk (top 10%) according to the COVID-19 Economic Risk Assessment Dashboard.

funding_code: (WWA PROGRAM AREA) TAT GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development initiative will be used to provide financial support for the development of a rural community laboratory training program for water operations personnel. This program will improve operations of small and very small drinking water systems and assist with achieving and maintaining compliance with legislation by providing recognized and accredited training for drinking water system samplers and Grade 1 and 2 laboratory personnel. OCTWQA proposes to provide both laboratory bench training and then certify water distribution system samplers and Grade 1 and 2 laboratory personnel.

These systems will be generating 400 kw of electricity that will be used for plant operations and over 1,500 kilowatt (kW) of thermal energy to be used for feedstock drying. This proposal would help with forest treatment for forest health, reduce greenhouse gases and provide improved fire safety to the local residents. The project will create 24 jobs.
